<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="spatial-accessibility">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>Design AR/VR/MR interfaces that work across motor, visual, cognitive, and motion-sensitivity differences. Every interaction needs two input modalities, a non-spatial fallback, and seated-mode parity.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>spatial-computing</tag>
      <tag>accessibility</tag>
      <tag>xr</tag>
      <tag>aria</tag>
      <tag>input-modalities</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Spatial Accessibility</title>
    <summary>A methodology for designing AR/VR/MR interfaces that work across motor, visual, cognitive, and motion-sensitivity differences. Every spatial interaction must support at least two input modalities and have a non-spatial fallback. Seated-mode parity is mandatory — if an interaction requires standing or arm-raising, a seated alternative must be documented.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Spatial UI introduces accessibility barriers that standard WCAG 2.2 does not address: six-degrees-of-freedom movement, implicit hand-tracking assumptions, immersive field-of-view constraints, and motion sickness. Platform review guidelines (Apple HIG, Meta VRC.PC.UX) include accessibility checks; failure blocks store approval and poses injury risk in enterprise XR contexts.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Designing AR/VR/MR experiences on Vision Pro, Quest, PS VR2, HoloLens, or WebXR.</item>
        <item>Adapting an existing flat UI for a spatial platform — need seated mode, gaze fallback, motion-comfort settings.</item>
        <item>Submitting an app to App Store or Meta Horizon Store.</item>
        <item>Designing enterprise XR (industrial training, medical) where injury risk is non-zero.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>2D mobile/desktop apps — use standard WCAG 2.2 / mobile a11y; spatial tradeoffs do not apply.</item>
        <item>Pure passthrough video apps with no UI overlay — accessibility reduces to standard video a11y (captions, contrast).</item>
        <item>Throwaway VR demos for a single internal user — full spatial-a11y program is overkill before validation.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="input-modality-matrix">
      <p>Every spatial interaction must support at least two independent input modalities; one must not be gaze-and-dwell if hand tracking is the primary. Provide a non-spatial fallback (flat-window mode, companion app, or voice-only path) for every critical user flow.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Every spatial interaction must support at least two independent input modalities; one must not be gaze-and-dwell if hand tracking is the primary.</statement>
        <rationale>Motor limitations, gloves, controllers-only environments, and hand-tracking failures all eliminate single-modality paths. Two independent modalities ensure at least one remains viable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Provide a non-spatial fallback (flat-window mode, companion app, or voice-only path) for every critical user flow.</statement>
        <rationale>Users unable to tolerate immersion or lacking the physical space for room-scale interaction cannot be excluded from core functionality.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Select object: gaze-and-pinch (primary), voice command "select" (secondary), controller trigger (tertiary). Flat-window fallback for seated users without hand tracking.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad">
        <note>Select object: grab gesture only. No alternative; users with motor impairment or low-FOV devices are locked out.</note>
      </example>
      <templates>
        <template path="templates/alt-input-matrix.ts" purpose="TypeScript auditor: checks each interaction has minimum 2 input modalities"/>
      </templates>
    </section>
    <section name="seated-mode">
      <p>Every interaction that works standing must also work from a seated position; document any exception with an explicit accommodation alternative. Reposition UI to seated eye-height (approximately 1.0-1.2 m above ground) when seated mode is active; do not require the user to look up beyond 20° above horizontal.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Every interaction that works standing must also work from a seated position; document any exception with an explicit accommodation alternative.</statement>
        <rationale>Enterprise XR, rehabilitation contexts, and users with mobility impairments require seated-mode parity. "Designed for standing" without a seated path excludes a legally-protected population in regulated industries.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Reposition UI to seated eye-height (approximately 1.0-1.2 m above ground) when seated mode is active; do not require the user to look up beyond 20° above horizontal.</statement>
        <rationale>Sustained upward head tilt causes neck fatigue within minutes; ergonomic guidelines for standing-height UI are not appropriate in seated contexts.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="comfort-and-captions">
      <p>Offer both vignette and teleport locomotion; never force a single comfort solution — comfort is individually variable. Default spatial captions to head-locked subtitles at 3 m apparent distance; provide a world-locked option with size and contrast controls. Provide audio descriptions for all cinematic and interactive XR moments that convey meaning through visuals alone.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Offer both vignette and teleport locomotion; never force a single comfort solution — comfort is individually variable.</statement>
        <rationale>Motion sickness triggers differ per user. Smooth locomotion causes nausea in some; snap-turn triggers others. Configurable options are the only reliable accommodation.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Default spatial captions to head-locked subtitles at 3 m apparent distance; provide a world-locked option with size and contrast controls.</statement>
        <rationale>Head-locked captions are readable in motion but break immersion. World-locked captions are immersive but unreadable during fast motion. Defaults favour readability; override favours immersion.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Provide audio descriptions for all cinematic and interactive XR moments that convey meaning through visuals alone.</statement>
        <rationale>VoiceOver on visionOS covers only partial screen content; hand-authored audio descriptions remain required for blind users in immersive contexts.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Use one subagent to map every interaction to the alternative-input matrix (gaze, voice, hand, controller, switch), a second to audit comfort settings and seated-mode coverage, and a third to generate audio descriptions and caption placement specs. Always validate on hardware with users — synthetic testing misses motion sickness and field-of-view blind spots.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Require hardware testing with at least five users including one low-vision, one motor-impaired, and one motion-sensitive tester before claiming spatial accessibility compliance.</statement>
        <rationale>No automated tool or agent can substitute for real user validation in spatial contexts. Comfort settings that "feel fine" to designers routinely fail real users with vestibular disorders.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="subagent-prompt-pattern">
      <example type="good">
        <note>Interaction audit prompt: "For each spatial interaction, return JSON: { name, primary_input, alternatives[], requires_motion: bool, comfort_options[], seated_compatible: bool, blockers[] }. Required alternatives: at least one of {gaze+dwell, voice, single-hand, controller, switch}. If requires_motion, comfort_options must include vignette, teleport, snap-turn, FOV-reduce, or seated."</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <p>LLMs default to controller-only assumptions without enumerating alternatives. Models conflate VR (fully immersive) and AR (passthrough overlay); accessibility tradeoffs differ. Caption placement reasoning is poor in current LLMs; agents recommend "head-locked" universally. Synthetic XR a11y testing tools are immature; do not declare compliance without hardware testing with real assistive users.</p>
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs defaulting to controller-only assumptions without enumerating alternatives explicitly.</description>
        <reason>Controllers are unavailable or unusable in many spatial contexts. Force the agent to enumerate all modality alternatives for each interaction rather than assuming a default input path.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent recommending head-locked HUD as a standard pattern from older XR literature.</description>
        <reason>Apple HIG visionOS forbids head-locked UI; Meta guidelines strongly discourage it for non-telemetry use. Current guidance is the opposite of legacy XR documentation that LLMs were trained on.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Declaring spatial accessibility compliance without hardware testing on real assistive users.</description>
        <reason>Synthetic XR a11y testing tools are immature. Motion sickness is individually variable and cannot be detected by static analysis. Only real-user hardware testing produces valid compliance evidence.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent recommending head-locked captions universally without considering immersion context.</description>
        <reason>Caption placement reasoning is poor in current LLMs. Head-locked captions are readable but break immersion; world-locked captions are immersive but unreadable in motion. Heuristics plus human review are required.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="platform-notes">
      <list>
        <item>WCAG does not fully cover spatial UI; W3C XAUR (XR Accessibility User Requirements) is informative, not normative — checklists must be authored by hand.</item>
        <item>VoiceOver on visionOS is partial; hand-authored audio descriptions are still required for blind users.</item>
        <item>Interaction zones must scale to accommodate hand size, dominance, and tremor — treat these as first-class input variables.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Default seated-mode parity: every interaction must work seated; if not, document an explicit alternative.</item>
        <item>Provide both vignette and teleport for any locomotion; let the user pick — no single solution fixes nausea universally.</item>
        <item>Treat hand size, dominance, and tremor as first-class input variables, not edge cases — interaction zones must scale.</item>
        <item>Caption styles per platform: head-locked subtitles default ON; world-locked optional with size/contrast slider.</item>
        <item>Recruit testers with motion sensitivity, low vision, and motor differences early — comfort tuning that "feels fine" to designers fails real users.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.w3.org/TR/xaur/">W3C XAUR (XR Accessibility User Requirements)</link>
